En primer lugar, la pandemia a tenido un fuerte efecto sobre las cadenas de suministro, y por lo mismo ha generado problemas para conseguir partes y piezas así como para distribuir los productos ya terminados. Esto se ha traducido en mayores costos de distribución y una evidente ralentización de los procesos. Por otra parte, tenemos el efecto ecnómico sobre los consumidores. La mayor parte de la población ha recibido un duro impacto a su nivel de ingresos, por lo tanto, se esperaría una reducción importante en el consumo de artículos no escenciales, entre ellos los iPhones. Si bien los procesos de vacunación han avanzado con rapidez y actualmente Estados Unidos está administrando 3.3 milllones de dosis al día. De acuerdo al simulador de Reuters, recién para Octubre de 2021 toda la población estadounidense habría recibido la 2da dosis. Esto deja un margen muy cerrado para que la economía alcance a recuperarse durante este año. Por otro lado, tenemos la relación de EEUU con China. Ya que, por un lado, el gigánte asiático, que pareciera haber controlado completamente la pandemia, es un gran consumidor de Iphones, lo que podría considerarse una buena noticia para Apple. Sin embargo, actualmente existe una guerra comercial entre ambos países (recordemos en caso de Huawei) y China ya ha dado muestras de que puede tomar contra medidas en respuesta a las restricciones que le ha impuesto el país americano.

Bumping up my initial forecast following strong Q1 numbers from Apple that were particularly driven by iPhone sales. The introduction of the iPhone 12 during the last quarter helped to fuel record quarterly revenue for Apple. Q1 sales for this quarter far outpaced those during the same time of FY19 giving Apple a good head start to see an increase in iPhone net sales following another decline in FY20. Additionally, strong global sales, especially in China and India, buoy the possibility of strong FY21 sales.

Currently, iPhone unit shipments are predicted to be around or about 230 million in fiscal 2021, with expectations for about 86 million to 87 million units to be shipped in the December quarter. This would mean a 20% year-over-year increase in unit shipments, resulting in fiscal 2021 revenue and EPS that are well above the consensus. Coupled with the decreasing cost of iPhone XR, 11, and introduction of an iPhone 12 - mini, there are plenty of options for buyers, especially if the globe begins to emerge financially sound from the COVID-19 pandemic.

Privacy activists noyb ("none of your business") have sued Apple for alleged privacy breach and wants to force the company to remove their Identifier for Advertisers (IDFA) from their appliances, esp. iPhones. IDFA is automatically generated when the iPhone is installed for the first time - without knowledge or consent of users. Although not directly linked to turnover or profit of Apple and their iPhone business, this lawsuit could delay any delivery of appliances - newest or older generations - to European consumers, since Apple would have to either ask the user for consent or remove the IDFA routine from their European iOS version. I wonder if millions of iPhones would be marketable as planned without update at all. https://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/web/apple-aktivisten-reichen-beschwerde-wegen-werbe-tracking-auf-iphones-ein-a-5a83891e-e811-4e23-b201-82809c460508

Apple is encountering challenges with supply chains and if the global economy continues to suffer due to covid, people won’t have the money to buy iPhones while they can buy cheaper high quality phones. Their iPad market may go higher.

- According to Bloomberg, Apple Inc. has asked suppliers to build at least 75 million 5G iPhones for later this year, roughly in line with last year’s launch, which means that despite the pandemic situation they expect to have at least the same levels of sales than the previous year. - While the Covid-19 outbreak has worsened the global economy, Apple is having a strong demand for iPhones, iPads and Mac computers from people working and studying remotely. - Despite this, I don't think that the revenues will be higher than those got in 2019.

FY 2019 appears to have been consistent with the average since FY 2016 - ~$140B. Spikes in the last couple of years have been in FY 2018 and FY 2015. I have not been able to unpack whether the models released in those years corresponded to models with significant feature upgrades. I am going to make an educated guess and say that is probably true - happy to be corrected :-). That would point to the first 5G IPhone causing a similar spike. The complicating factor of course is COVID. However even with the COVID hit in FY 2020 there was only a 3% hit to sales - it wasn't catastrophic. If we had a similar hit next year, but the ~say 10% boost from the new model (it was 18% in FY 2018), we would still be ~4% above FY2019. I see that as a decent margin of error. Regarding the probability estimate I would say I am confident it is greater than 60-40, but not as high as 90-10. Something around 70-30, and 80-20 seems right. Because of the small risk of supply disruption I will go for the lower value
Thanks to @DNK89 for giving the sources informing this prediction.

The last factor is this newly released phone does not feature exciting new advancements and I do not think that will drive consumers to upgrade their current phones.

Apple's 4Q 10-K filing identifies lower iPhone sales in 2020 than 2019 due to 1) fewer models; 2) store closings; 3) exchange rates impacting non-US sales. 1) Fewer models: I agree with @tfk. More models will allow apple to reach more consumers (but possibly hurt margins). 2) FY 2021 will hopefully see fewer lockdowns than 2020. Also, I expect FY2020 caused a lot of people to defer upgrading or purchasing a new iPhone. This might push people to upgrade in FY2021. 3) Exchange rates and sales in developing countries will be something to monitor into the future. IMO, this is not an important factor impacting sales in FY2021.
